/*
:name: latch_icg
:type: equiv
:verilog_top: latch_icg.icg
:pyrope_top: icg
*/

// LIVE equiv test (promoted 2026-07-20, todo/livehd/2f-latch) — THE REAL-WORLD
// SHAPE. An integrated clock gate: a transparent-low latch samples the enable
// while the clock is low, and the gated clock is `clk & enl`. The latch is
// there to make the enable glitch-free; this is the canonical latch application
// and it is what `prim_clk_gate` in core-et is, whose UNKNOWN cascades up
// through the whole minion full-design LEC. This pair guards the ICG STRUCTURE
// end to end (prp -> tolg -> cgen -> lgcheck).
//
// What it does NOT guard — the two live clock-soundness bugs, which need
// event-driven or clock-aware checkers (2f-latch M4/M5; lgcheck itself is
// edge- and gate-blind for flops, so an equiv PASS here says nothing about
// what the gated clock DOES):
//   * LEC never reads `clock_pin`/`posclk` (pass/lec/encode.cpp), so it FALSELY
//     PROVES a gated-clock flop equivalent to an ungated one — tracked by
//     lhd/tests/lec_clock_blindness_test.sh;
//   * sim computes the gate expression as DEAD CODE and advances the flop every
//     cycle anyway — tracked by tests/fixme/flop_sim_gated_clock.prp.
// Under 2f-latch M4 the ICG is folded into a clock-enable on the driven flops as
// a BOTH-SIDES normalization (never a one-sided abstraction). Nobody proves ICGs
// in industry practice; they normalize them away.
pub mod icg(clk:bool, en:bool) -> (gclk:bool@[0]) {
  reg enl:bool:[latch=true]
  if !clk {
    enl = en
  }
  gclk = clk and enl
}
